LAGOS  – BUA Foods has published its N79.7bn turnover unaudited report for 9 months ended September 30, 2021 while profit after tax grew 6.7 per cent year on year to N16.6 billion. According to the report, total turnover rose 6.8 per cent year on year to N79.7 billion in the period on the back of a 152.6 per cent surge in sales of Non-fortified sugar with a 72.2 per cent turnover. Nonetheless, gross margin logged at 28.4 per cent in the 9 months of 2021 from 28.6 per cent in the same period of 2020, due to the faster pace of growth in cost of sales (+7.2% to N57.1bn) than revenue. Further down, EBIT stood at N22.4 billion (+18.1% y/y) with expansion in margin to 28.1 per cent from 25.4 per cent. SMEs Workshop Will Bridge Participants’ Gaps On Production… FCMB’s FastCash Offers Up To N200,000 Support For School Fees,… Also, BUA Foods reported a 69.6 per cent growth in finance cost (N5.8bn) while profit after tax grew 6.7 per cent year on year to N16.6 billion. Meanwhile the stock market recouped losses at the start of the week as the NGX ASI gained 0.6% to close at 44,655.89 points, buoyed by gains in BUACEMENT (+2.0%), GTCO (+1.4%), and ACCESS (+2.1%). As a result, YTD return improved to 4.5% while market capitalisation increased N138.1bn to N24.1tn. Volume traded rose 9.8% to 235.2m units while value traded fell 28.7% to N1.9bn. TRANSCORP (38.1m units), GTCO (18.7m units), and JAIZBANK (15.0m units) led by volume while GTCO (N476.5m), FBNH (N161.1m), and NIGERIAN BREWERIES (N146.2m) led by value. Across sectors within our coverage, performance was uneven as 3 indices advanced, 2 lost while the AFR-ICT index closed flat. The Banking index led the gainers, up to 1.0%, due to upswing in prices of GTCO (+1.4%) and ACCESS (+2.1%). Trailing, the Consumer Goods and Oil & Gas indices rose 0.7% and 0.3% respectively on account of gains in BUAFOODS (+4.2%), DANGSUGAR (+7.4%), ETERNA (+5.8%) and CONOIL (+3.1%). Conversely, the Insurance and Industrial Goods indices dipped 1.6% and 2bps respectively on price decline in NEM (-8.3%), WAPIC (-3.9%) and WAPCO (-0.4%).